  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "PmWyQ6QlTSf/oeAqbAkWSWCqOpM=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## UX entry point\n\nLive collaboration is surfaced through a **Collaborate tab in the chat panel**, not through any editor chrome.\n\n## Flow\n\n1. Pick a **drive or doc** as the collaboration target.\n2. **Multi-select participants by Swarm ID**, reusing the document-share picker pattern.\n3. Invitation is delivered as a **chat card** with `[Join]` / `[Decline]` buttons.\n4. An **active collabs list** shows participant avatars and a last-activity timestamp.\n\n## Explicit non-goal\n\n**No editor-level UI work.** No cursor overlays, no caret labels, no per-editor presence widgets. The toolbar's existing History view -- auto-refreshed when a GSOC `op-committed` ping debounces in -- is the entire presence surface.\n\n## Why this shape\n\nReusing the document-share picker keeps the mental model consistent: collaboration is a natural extension of sharing, addressed by Swarm ID, negotiated via a chat card. It avoids building per-editor UI for a set of editors (tables, visual canvases, dashboards, button grids) where no shared cursor metaphor would generalize.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z"
    }
  },
